===Verb===
{{en-verb|abridg}}

# {{lb|en|transitive|archaic}} To [[deprive]]; to [[cut off]]. {{defdate|First attested from around (1150 to 1350)}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=8}}</ref>
# {{lb|en|transitive|archaic|rare}} To [[debar]] from. {{defdate|First attested from around (1150 to 1350)}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To make [[shorter]]; to [[shorten]] in [[duration]] or [[extent]]. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470)}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|passage=The bridegroom ... '''abridged''' his visit.|author=Smollett}}
#* {{quote-book|passage=She retired herself to Sebaste, and '''abridged''' her train from state to necessity.|author=Fuller}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To shorten or contract by using [[fewer]] [[word]]s, yet [[retaining]] the [[sense]]; to [[epitomize]]; to [[condense]]{{defdate|First attested in 1384.}}<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=4}}</ref>. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470)}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* '''1911''', ''{{w|1911 Encyclopædia Britannica}}'' - ''Johnson, Samuel''
#*: It was still necessary for the man who had been formerly saluted by the highest authority as dictator of the English language to supply his wants by constant toil. He '''abridged''' his Dictionary. He proposed to bring out an edition of Shakespeare by subscription, and many subscribers sent in their names and laid down their money; but he soon found the task so little to his taste that he turned to more attractive employments. 
#* '''1891''', {{w|Henry Melville}}, ''Billy Budd'' Chapter 3
#*:Such an episode in the Island's grand naval story her naval historians naturally '''abridge'''; one of them (G.P.R. James) candidly acknowledging that fain would he pass it over did not "impartiality forbid fastidiousness."
# {{lb|en|transitive}} Cut short; [[truncate]]. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470)}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[curtail]]. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470)}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: {{ux|en|He had his rights '''abridged''' by the crooked sheriff.}}

====Usage notes====
* {{sense|deprive}} Usually used with '''to''' or sometimes with '''from''' as, to '''abridge''' one of his rights.

